Rather than using `is_fallback_fn` I'm think we could clean this up using the following pattern.

```
class fallback_fn:
    pass


def encode_transaction_data(abi, web3, fn_identifier, args=None, kwargs=None):
    if fn_identifier is fallback_fn:
        fn_abi, fn_selector, fn_arguments = get_fallback_function_info(...)
    elif is_text(fn_identifier):
        fn_abi, fn_selector, fn_arguments = get_function_info(...)
    else:
        raise TypeError("Unsupported function identifier")

    ...
```

The *new* `get_fallback_function_info` handles all the special cases that were previously handled by `is_fallback` and the `get_function_info` remains simple with less logic forks.

The `fallback_fn` class simply serves as an unambiguous identifier for when we want to specify the fallback function, removing the need for the *extra* flag as well as the need to validate that we aren't passing in both `fn_name` and `is_fallback_fn == True`.

Does this make sense?

@jph00 If I get @mcskinner the whole point of this function is to apply a `f` on a pythonic structure of objects including `tensors` ,  `ndarrays`, `DataSets` (which are `Iterable`)

This seems to be very useful especially if we allow for nesting of structures, imagine:
```py
>>> ds = trn_ds, val_ds, tst_ds
>>> sapply(ds, DataLoader)    # -> (trn_dl, val_dl, tst_dl)

>>> sapply( (x, [mask, borders, weights]), crop)  #-> (corp(x), [crop(mask), crop(borders), crop(weights)])
```

Then the name `sapply` seems to  reflect the idea well as it can be read as "structure apply". Which explains why the function don't work on any`Iterable` and only on list tuples nad dicts and why `sapply(obj, f)`  is  `f(obj)` and not `map(obj, f)` (ie. because obj is not embedded in  a pythonic structure)

Such function can simplify  `get_tensor` from data loaders for example:
https://github.com/fastai/fastai/blob/master/fastai/dataloader.py#L10-L20

If we make sapply as follows:
```py
def sapply(x, f):
    if isinstance(x, collections.Mapping):
        return {k: sapply(sample, f) for k, sample in x.items()}
    elif isinstance(x, collections.List):
        return [sapply(sample, f) for sample in x]
    elif isinstance(x, collections.Tuple):
        return tuple(sapply(sample, f) for sample in x)
    else:
        return f(x)
```    
    
We can write:
```py
def pin_memory(batch):
    if isinstance(batch, (np.ndarray, np.generic)):
